Insurancerating

This Notebook demonstrates the use of the insurancerating package. The package helps to implement GLMs by executing all steps needed to construct a risk premium from the data.

It provides a data driven strategy for the construction of tariff classes in P&C insurance.

The goal is to bin the continuous factors, to then produce categorical risk factors which capture the effect of the covariate on the response in an accurate way, while being easy to use in a generalized linear model (GLM).

1. Package Demonstration

Following the README instructions on the github package

Insurancerating requires each row to be each policy. Policy claims already fulfils this requirement. Furthermore, the dataset policy_claims is primarily categorical.

MTPL demonstration

GAM Techniques

How to fit a GAM

```r
# Claim frequency 
age_policyholder_frequency <- 
  fit_gam(data = MTPL, 
          nclaims = nclaims, 
          x = age_policyholder, 
          exposure = exposure)

# Claim severity 
age_policyholder_severity <- 
  fit_gam(data = MTPL, 
          nclaims = nclaims, 
          x = age_policyholder, 
          exposure = exposure, 
          amount = amount, 
          model = \severity\)

autoplot(age_policyholder_frequency, show_observations = T)

### Adding Constructed tariff classes

Add tariff classes for the variable `age_policyholder` to the dataset, and set the base level of the factor to the level with the largest exposure. 

`biggest_reference` specifies the first level of a factor to the level with the largest exposure. Afterwards, sorted by alphabetical ordering. 

In this example, ages (39, 50] has highest exposure.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZGF0IDwtIE1UUEwgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZShhZ2VfcG9saWN5aG9sZGVyX2ZyZXFfY2F0ID0gY2x1c3RlcnNfZnJlcSR0YXJpZmZfY2xhc3NlcykgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZShhY3Jvc3Mod2hlcmUoaXMuY2hhcmFjdGVyKSwgYXMuZmFjdG9yKSkgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZShhY3Jvc3Mod2hlcmUoaXMuZmFjdG9yKSwgfmJpZ2dlc3RfcmVmZXJlbmNlKC4sIGV4cG9zdXJlKSkpXG5cbmdsaW1wc2UoZGF0KVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

  nclaims ~ age_policyholder_freq_cat, 
  offset = log(exposure), 
  family = \poisson\, data = dat)

  nclaims ~ age_policyholder_freq_cat + age_policyholder,
  offset = log(exposure), 
  family = \poisson\, data = dat)

### Bootstrapping

To test the variance of the RMSE, compute the RMSE from generated bootstrap replicates. This is mainly for claim severity models, in case the portfolio contains large claim sizes. 

Example below shows the variation of RMSE of the frequency model is low, where the dashed line shows the RMSE of the original fitted model. 


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuYm9vdHN0cmFwX3Jtc2UobW9kZWxfZnJlcTEsIGRhdCwgbiA9IDEwMCwgc2hvd19wcm9ncmVzcyA9IEZBTFNFKSAlPiUgXG4gIGF1dG9wbG90KC4pXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
bootstrap_rmse(model_freq1, dat, n = 100, show_progress = FALSE) %>% 
  autoplot(.)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


### Poisson Overdispersion

A dispersion ratio larger than 1 indicates overdispersion, where the observed variance is higher than the variance of the theoretical model. Otherwise, if it is close to 1, a Poisson model fits well.

* p-value < 0.05 indicates overdispersion
* Overdispersion > 2 indicates a larger problem with data, perhaps outliers


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2hlY2tfb3ZlcmRpc3BlcnNpb24obW9kZWxfZnJlcTEpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
check_overdispersion(model_freq1)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

### Residuals

`check_residuals` standardizes the residuals to be between 0 and 1. This is achieved by a simulation-based approach. 

Detect deviations from the expected distribution, and produce a uniform quantile-quantile plot. The simulated residuals in the QQ plot below show no clear deviation from a Poisson distribution. Note that formal tests almost always yield significant results for the distribution of residuals and visual inspections (e.g. Q-Q plots) are preferable.



<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2hlY2tfcmVzaWR1YWxzKG1vZGVsX2ZyZXExLCBuX3NpbXVsYXRpb25zID0gMTAwMCkgJT4lXG4gIGF1dG9wbG90KC4pXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r

  autoplot(.)

## MTPL2: Univariate Analysis

Analysing one single variable. An univariate analysis consists in the evaluation of overall claim frequency, severity and risk premium. Its main purpose lies in verifying the experience data reasonableness using previous experience comparison and professional judgement.

`univariate()` shows the basic risk indicators split by the levels of the discrete risk factor:


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxudW5pdmFyaWF0ZShcbiAgTVRQTDIsIFxuICB4ID0gYXJlYSwgIyBkaXNjcmV0ZSByaXNrIGZhY3RvclxuICBuY2xhaW1zID0gbmNsYWltcywgIyBudW1iZXIgb2YgY2xhaW1zXG4gIGV4cG9zdXJlID0gZXhwb3N1cmUsIFxuICBwcmVtaXVtID0gcHJlbWl1bSwgXG4gIHNldmVyaXR5ID0gYW1vdW50KSAjIGxvc3NcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
univariate(
  MTPL2, 
  x = area, # discrete risk factor
  nclaims = nclaims, # number of claims
  exposure = exposure, 
  premium = premium, 
  severity = amount) # loss

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


The following indicators are calculated:

1. frequency (i.e. frequency = number of claims / exposure)
2. average_severity (i.e. average severity = severity / number of claims)
3. risk_premium (i.e. risk premium = severity / exposure = frequency x average severity)
4. loss_ratio (i.e. loss ratio = severity / premium)
5. average_premium (i.e. average premium = premium / exposure)

The term risk premium is equivalent to pure premium and burning cost. 

`univariate` ignores missing input arguments. For example, only claim freq is calculated when `premium` and `severity` are unknown. 


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxudW5pdmFyaWF0ZShNVFBMMiwgeCA9IGFyZWEsIG5jbGFpbXMgPSBuY2xhaW1zLCBleHBvc3VyZSA9IGV4cG9zdXJlKSBcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
univariate(MTPL2, x = area, nclaims = nclaims, exposure = exposure) 

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

## MTPL Modelling

Below shows model refinement to impose either smoothing to the parameter estimates, or to add restrictions to the parameter estimates. 


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxubW9kX2ZyZXEgPC0gZ2xtKG5jbGFpbXMgfiB6aXAgKyBhZ2VfcG9saWN5aG9sZGVyX2ZyZXFfY2F0LCBcbiAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICBvZmZzZXQgPSBsb2coZXhwb3N1cmUpLCBcbiAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICBmYW1pbHkgPSBcXHBvaXNzb25cXCwgXG4gICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgZGF0YSA9IGRhdClcblxubW9kX3NldiA8LSBnbG0oYW1vdW50IH4gYm0gKyB6aXAsIFxuICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgd2VpZ2h0cyA9IG5jbGFpbXMsIFxuICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgZmFtaWx5ID0gR2FtbWEobGluayA9IFxcbG9nXFwpLCBcbiAgICAgICAgICAgICAgIGRhdGEgPSBkYXQgJT4lIGZpbHRlcihhbW91bnQgPiAwKSlcblxuTVRQTF9wcmVtaXVtIDwtIGRhdCAlPiVcbiAgYWRkX3ByZWRpY3Rpb24obW9kX2ZyZXEsIG1vZF9zZXYpICU+JVxuICBtdXRhdGUocHJlbWl1bSA9IHByZWRfbmNsYWltc19tb2RfZnJlcSAqIHByZWRfYW1vdW50X21vZF9zZXYpXG5cblxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
mod_freq <- glm(nclaims ~ zip + age_policyholder_freq_cat, 
                offset = log(exposure), 
                family = \poisson\, 
                data = dat)

mod_sev <- glm(amount ~ bm + zip, 
               weights = nclaims, 
               family = Gamma(link = \log\), 
               data = dat %>% filter(amount > 0))

MTPL_premium <- dat %>%
  add_prediction(mod_freq, mod_sev) %>%
  mutate(premium = pred_nclaims_mod_freq * pred_amount_mod_sev)


<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Fit a burning model without restrictions. Even though restrictions could be applied to frequency and severity models, it is more appropriate to add restrictions (and smoothing) to the risk premium model.

* Burning cost: the ratio of incurred losses within a specified amount in excess of the theoretical amount of premium it would take only to cover losses.

  * Used to ascertain the rates for EoL Reinsurance
  * Divide excess loss by the total subject premium
  

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuYnVybl91bnJlc3RyaWN0ZWQgPC0gZ2xtKHByZW1pdW0gfiB6aXAgKyBibSArIGFnZV9wb2xpY3lob2xkZXJfZnJlcV9jYXQsIFxuICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgIHdlaWdodHMgPSBleHBvc3VyZSwgXG4gICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgZmFtaWx5ID0gR2FtbWEobGluayA9IFxcbG9nXFwpLCBcbiAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICBkYXRhID0gTVRQTF9wcmVtaXVtKSBcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
burn_unrestricted <- glm(premium ~ zip + bm + age_policyholder_freq_cat, 
                         weights = exposure, 
                         family = Gamma(link = \log\), 
                         data = MTPL_premium) 

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


### Rate Smoothing

Smoothing can be used to reduce the tolerance for rate change. In `smooth_coef()`:
* `x_cut` is the name of the risk factor with clusters
* `x_org` is the name of the original risk factor, 
* `degree` is the order of the polynomial, 
* `breaks` is a numerical vector with new clusters for `x_org`. 

The smoothed estimates are added as an offset term to the
model. An offset is just a fixed term added to the linear predictor, therefore if there is already an offset in the model, the offset terms are added together first
(i.e. offset = log(*a*) + log(*b*) = log(*a**b*)).


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuYnVybl91bnJlc3RyaWN0ZWQgJT4lXG4gIHNtb290aF9jb2VmKHhfY3V0ID0gXFxhZ2VfcG9saWN5aG9sZGVyX2ZyZXFfY2F0XFwsIFxuICAgICAgICAgICAgICB4X29yZyA9IFxcYWdlX3BvbGljeWhvbGRlclxcLCBcbiAgICAgICAgICAgICAgYnJlYWtzID0gc2VxKDE4LCA5NSwgNSkpICU+JVxuICBhdXRvcGxvdCgpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
burn_unrestricted %>%
  smooth_coef(x_cut = \age_policyholder_freq_cat\, 
              x_org = \age_policyholder\, 
              breaks = seq(18, 95, 5)) %>%
  autoplot()

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

```r
prop_dat <- policy_claims%>%
  filter(!LossofIncome_cover)%>%
  select(-contains(\lossofinc\))

prop_cat_variables <- colnames(prop_dat)[c(8:15, 17)]

univ_prop <- 
  tibble(var_analysis = prop_cat_variables)%>%
  mutate(univ_df = map(
    var_analysis, 
    ~univariate(prop_dat,
           x = vec_ext(.), 
           nclaims = claimcount_prop,
           exposure = exposure,
           severity = grossincurred_prop)))

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

prop_sumins_freq <- fit_gam(
  data = prop_dat,
  nclaims = claimcount_prop,
  x = suminsured_prop,
  exposure = exposure
)

prop_sumins_severity <- fit_gam(
  data = prop_dat,
  nclaims = claimcount_prop,
  x = suminsured_prop,
  exposure = exposure,
  amount = grossincurred_prop,
  model = \severity\
)

```r
prop_loi_dat <- policy_claims%>%
  filter(LossofIncome_cover)%>%
  select(-contains(\lossofinc\))

prop_loi_cat_variables <- colnames(prop_loi_dat)[c(8:15, 17)]

univ_prop_loi <- 
  tibble(var_analysis = prop_loi_cat_variables)%>%
  mutate(univ_df = map(
    var_analysis, 
    ~univariate(prop_loi_dat,
           x = vec_ext(.), 
           nclaims = claimcount_prop,
           exposure = exposure,
           severity = grossincurred_prop)))

<!-- rnb-source-end -->
